  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "It is caused by the\nEpstein-Barr virus\n(EBV)\nMost commonly seen in immunocompromised individuals, and has a high specificity for individuals with\nHIV\n/AIDs.\nThe white plaque appearance is due to hyperkeratosis and epithelial hyperplasia.",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "Epstein-Barr virus",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Epstein-Barr_virus"
        },
        {
          "text": "HIV",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/HIV"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Characterized by white plaques over the lateral sides of the tongue.\nUnlike\noropharyngeal candidiasis\n, the white plaques are unable to be scraped off.\nUnlike other forms of leukoplakia, it is NOT a precancerous lesion\nIt is asymptomatic, with most patients presenting over concern for aesthetic appearance",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "oropharyngeal candidiasis",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Oropharyngeal_candidiasis"
        }
      ]
    },
